solutionCode.javascript:
    ```javascript
function maxScore(points) {
    let m = points.length, n = points[0].length;
    let dp = [points[0]];

    for (let r = 1; r < m; r++) {
        dp.push(Array(n).fill(0));
        for (let c = 0; c < n; c++) {
            let score = points[r][c];
            for (let c_prev = 0; c_prev < n; c_prev++) {
                dp[r][c] = Math.max(dp[r][c], dp[r - 1][c_prev] + score - Math.abs(c - c_prev));
            }
        }
    }

    return Math.max(...dp[m - 1]);
}
```


    The algorithm uses dynamic programming. The `dp` array has the same dimensions as the input matrix, `m` rows and `n` columns. The value `dp[r][c]` corresponds to the maximum score achievable when picking the cell at row `r` and column `c`. 

At the start, the first row of `dp` is initialized with the values of the corresponding first row of the input `points` matrix because there's no previous row.

For each subsequent row `r`, iterate through all its columns `c`, and calculate the maximum score of picking the cell at (r, c) by iterating through all possible previous column positions `c_prev` and using the following formula:

`dp[r][c] = max(dp[r - 1][c_prev] + current score - abs(c - c_prev))`

Where `current score = points[r][c]`. After filling the entire `dp` array, the maximum score achievable is the maximum value in the last row of the `dp` array.

